node.text:
Dating app company Match Group is swiping left on Texas' massively restrictive anti-abortion law. ⁠
⁠
The Dallas-based company, which is the parent org to dating apps like Tinder, OkCupid, and Hinge, circulated an internal memo announcing the formation of a fund that would help Texas-based employees and their dependents with expenses if they needed to seek abortions out of state. ⁠
⁠
In the internal email, obtained and reported on by the Dallas Morning News, CEO Shar Dubey stressed how the company usually avoids political stances 'unless relevant to our business,' but added that 'in this instance, I personally, as a woman in Texas, could not keep silent.' ⁠
⁠
Dubey, who emigrated from India to Texas more than 25 years ago, described the state's draconian anti-abortion law, S.B. 8, as ' more regressive than most of the world, including India.' ⁠
⁠
In addition to prohibiting abortions after just 6 weeks, even in cases of rape and incest, S.B. 8 also gives citizens—even complete strangers—the right to sue anyone who is deemed to have assisted in performing an abortion, from doctors to potentially even Uber drivers. In a 5-4 'shadow-docket' decision released late Wednesday night, the Supreme Court voted not to block the law in Texas—a decision many have seen as a direct hit to the legitimacy of Roe v. Wade.⁠
⁠
⁠
#match #matchgroup #texas #abortion

node.text:
Shortly before midnight EST on the night of Sept 1, the Supreme Court issued a ruling declining to block a Texas law banning abortions in the state after 6 weeks. The court’s decision to not block TX’s law was handed down 5-4, with only one conservative justice, John Roberts, siding with the liberal wing.

The decision was delivered via SCOTUS’ ‘shadow docket,’ a secretive process in which short, unsigned rulings are issued without oral arguments being heard ahead of time. The decision is a clear sign that the days of Roe v. Wade could be numbered. In addition to banning abortions at 6 weeks, the TX law makes no exception for rape or incest, though it does allow exceptions for ‘medical emergencies.’ Perhaps most radically, the law allows any private citizen, even complete strangers, to bring civil suits against anyone who assists in performing an abortion, from doctors to potentially even Uber drivers.

In her dissent, liberal Justice Sonia Sotomayor criticized the verdict, saying it effectively turns private citizens into ‘bounty hunters.’
